  "prompt": "Why are there two capital letters in the surname McCall?",
  "response": "The capital letter in the middle of the surname \"McCall\" is a convention derived from the Gaelic languages, specifically Scottish and Irish Gaelic. The \"Mc\" (or \"Mac\") is a prefix meaning \"son of.\" The capital letter following it indicates that it's a separate word element, the name of the father.\n\nSo, McCall means \"son of Call.\" The capital \"C\" distinguishes it as the name of the father, rather than just a lowercase letter that might blend into a longer word. It's a visual indicator of the Gaelic origin and the patronymic nature of the surname.\n",
